    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:02f094eb-bd6b-4017-9a96-43dfa1088145",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 9-year-old girl who appears tired, mildly ill, and mildly dehydrated, sitting curled forward on the exam chair and intermittently pressing a hand to her abdomen. Her lips are dry, her face is pale, and she asks for water frequently. She has had two days of frequent diarrhea with intermittent vomiting, and today her mother reports that one of the stools was streaked with blood and mucus, which prompted greater concern. She has been less playful than usual, preferring to lie on the couch wrapped in a blanket, but she remains alert, interactive, and appropriately responsive.\n\nHer illness began abruptly after a weekend birthday party where several children later developed similar gastrointestinal symptoms. Since then she has had crampy periumbilical abdominal pain, nausea, reduced appetite, low-grade fever, and repeated loose stools. The diarrhea has mostly been watery, but the new bloody stool suggests infectious colitis rather than simple dietary upset. She has urinated less frequently today and felt dizzy when standing, consistent with mild to moderate volume depletion. There is no severe focal abdominal pain, no confusion, and no profound lethargy.\n\n{patientName} lives with her mother, father, and younger brother in a suburban home and attends primary school, where she eats school cafeteria lunches and shares snacks and drinks with classmates more often than her parents would like. She enjoys soccer, drawing animals, sleepovers with friends, and summer swimming at a community pool; these activities and close contact with other children increase her exposure to common viral and foodborne gastrointestinal pathogens. She is usually energetic and sociable, with good school performance and regular physical activity.\n\nHer family is attentive and notes that she had a milder stomach-bug episode last year after a school picnic, though this illness is more severe. She also has seasonal allergic rhinitis and mild eczema, and in the past month she completed a course of amoxicillin for otitis media, a recent medication exposure that can increase susceptibility to infectious diarrhea. The family keeps a generally balanced diet, but she frequently eats buffet-style party foods, cafeteria meals, and convenience snacks at school events. Overall, {patientName} presents like a previously well child with acute infectious gastroenteritis/colitis, now showing early dehydration and a concerning episode of bloody diarrhea."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:63420963-ab86-4ff4-9a9b-cccecf6698f6",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has generally been healthy but does have seasonal allergic rhinitis and mild atopic eczema. One month ago she was treated with amoxicillin for acute otitis media, which is a relevant recent exposure because antibiotic use can alter gut flora and increase susceptibility to infectious diarrhea. She has never been hospitalized and has no history of inflammatory bowel disease or celiac disease. Immunizations are up to date for age according to her mother.\n\nHer current symptoms began about 36 hours ago with nausea and one episode of vomiting, followed by multiple loose watery stools overnight and through the next day. She has had low-grade fever at home, intermittent abdominal cramping, decreased oral intake, and reduced urine output. Although the stools were initially non-bloody, her mother reports a small amount of blood and mucus in one bowel movement this morning. There has been no bilious emesis and no recent travel or untreated water exposure.\n\nHer mother recalls one prior, milder episode of acute gastroenteritis after a school picnic last year that resolved with home fluids and did not require medical care. She currently takes no chronic prescription medications, but she uses cetirizine during allergy season and has received acetaminophen for fever with partial relief. The recent amoxicillin exposure may have contributed to increased vulnerability to infectious diarrhea in this episode.\n\n{patientName} attends primary school, eats some meals in the school cafeteria, and often participates in birthday parties, shared snacks, sleepovers, and community-pool swimming, all of which increase exposure to common enteric pathogens. She lives in a stable home environment with both parents and a younger sibling. Notably, her younger brother developed a brief diarrheal illness earlier this week, and her maternal aunt has a history of recurrent infectious colitis during childhood due to poor sanitation exposure in her home region, providing relevant family history of the same and related disorders."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
